    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:sec>\n                  <jats:title>Background</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>A large number of online COVID-19 symptom checkers and chatbots have been developed but anecdotal evidence suggests that their conclusions are highly variable. To our knowledge, no study has evaluated the accuracy of COVID-19 symptom checkers in a statistically rigorous manner.</jats:p>\n                </jats:sec>\n                <jats:sec>\n                  <jats:title>Methods</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>In this paper, we evaluate 10 different COVID-19 symptom checkers screening 50 COVID-19 case reports alongside 410 non-COVID-19 control cases.</jats:p>\n                </jats:sec>\n                <jats:sec>\n                  <jats:title>Results</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>\n                    We find that the number of correctly assessed cases varies considerably between different symptom checkers, with Symptoma (F\n                    <jats:sub>1</jats:sub>\n                    =0.92, MCC=0.85) showing the overall best performance followed by Infermedica (F\n                    <jats:sub>1</jats:sub>\n                    =0.80, MCC=0.61).\n                  </jats:p>\n                </jats:sec>",
